snippet.textDisplay:
Scenario: Pandemic and temporary? mask shortage.
Question: For the following device, what design aspects from the doctors POV would make it safer and easier to use than existing N95 masks?
Proposed device: Peltier cooler used as heat engine. one side hot. the other side cold. Air would pass through a radiator on the hot side to get above known viral kill temperature then pass through a similar radiator on the cold side before being inhaled to bring it down to a safe breathing temperature. This would allow a mechanical respirator to be used by many people safely, but also Doctors could use a PAPR with a continuous filter. The device could have a battery pack for limited? off grid use and an ac plug for doctors to plugin in each room. There are many other ways to heat and cool air, perhaps another reader will come up with a better heat&cool solution.

snippet.textDisplay: That N95 half mask does not protect against the infected air which comes out of someone's lungs as the air particle is less than .3 of a micron in size, thus passing through the mask. However,  if someone sneezes or coughs and a mist of body fluids come at you the mask will block the most as the virus is contained in the small particles which are larger than .3 of a micron in size and the N95 is rated by NIOSH (National Institutes for Occupational Safety and Health) to block 95% of that therefore it's possible that 5% of the airborne contaminate which is above .3 of a micron in size to get through the mask. CDC (Center for Disease Control), NIOSH and OSHA, etc., still don't know how much of the virus it takes to get a person sick with the disease.  That's why workers who are caring for those who have been confirmed to have Covid19 are still getting the disease and worse case, even dying.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm not sure if it has been mentioned in the comments before, but 34 states have laws against price gouging. Many of these laws take effect once a state of emergency has been declared nationally or on a state level for situations, such as a natural disaster or a medical emergency. The anti price-gouging laws typically cover any supplies that are considered "necessary". In this case, medical masks would definitely fall into the category of "necessary" supplies. Depending on the state you live in, the individuals you bought the masks from could be, and should be, prosecuted for profiteering during this medical  emergency. If there is a "next time",  the threat of criminal prosecution may help to get a better deal. If not, I would consider reporting them to the state attorney general. As a physician myself, I find this type criminal profiteering reprehensible.
